T1  - The Impact of Interviewer Effects on Skin Color Assessment in a Cross-National Context
AN  - 2431021306
AB  - There is a growing trend in national and international studies to measure respondents’ skin color as a supplement to traditional race classifications. Skin color measurements are often used as an explanatory variable in studies of social and racial inequalities (Bailey, Saperstein, & Penner, 2014; Flores & Telles, 2012; Hutchings, Jefferson, Lewis, & Yadon, 2015; Lerman, McCabe, & Sadin, 2015; Perreira & Telles, 2014; Telles & Paschel, 2014; Telles & Steele, 2012). Given its broad appeal, skin color is now collected in several large-scale surveys, such as the General Social Survey, the National Longitudinal Survey of Youth, the American National Election Studies, and the Latin American Public Opinion Project AmericasBarometer study. There are multiple ways to measure skin color, including reflectance spectrometers, which measure the amount of light reflected on an area of skin. However, for cost and other reasons, many surveys rely on interviewer assessments of respondents’ skin color (Telles & Lim, 1998; Villarreal, 2012). Despite the use of visual aids to calibrate judgments, scholars have expressed doubts regarding the quality of interviewer-ascribed measures of skin color (Hannon & DeFina, 2016; Hill, 2002; Villarreal, 2010, 2012). The extent to which interviewers introduce random and systematic error in skin color analyses is unknown. In this research note, we address these knowledge gaps using the 2010 Latin American Public Opinion Project AmericaBarometers study, a cross-national survey involving 26 countries and over 43,000 respondents. We apply a cross-classified multilevel model to separate interviewer- and area-effects and quantify the magnitude of these effects across countries. Specifically, we address the following research questions:What is the amount of variation in interviewer-ascribed skin color that can be attributed to interviewers and the areas they work in, within and between countries?How much of the between-interviewer variation in respondents’ skin color is explained by characteristics of the interviewer, including their own skin color?What is the magnitude of bias in substantive analyses of the association between Socio-Economic Status (SES) and skin color if interviewer effects are ignored?
